{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"26a63211-0472-4bd5-9413-8c88e499c456","content":"Here's my analysis of the evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## Evaluation Performance Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nProperty functions that perform file I/O execute during **every evaluation pass** (including IDE background evaluations). This blocks the evaluation thread on disk access.\n\n**Fix:** Read the file in a target at build time using `ReadLinesFromFile`, or use a source generator if needed at compile time.\n\n### 2. Expensive Recursive Glob (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the entire directory tree on every evaluation. If the directory grows (e.g., `node_modules`, large asset folders), this becomes increasingly expensive.\n\n**Fix:** Narrow the glob to specific extensions/directories, or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes` early.\n\n### 3. Chained Import Depth (Low Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of chained imports. Currently shallow, but this pattern scales poorly — deep import chains increase evaluation time and make preprocessing output harder to debug.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The biggest win is eliminating the `File::ReadAllText` property function. The recursive glob is the second priority, especially as the repo grows.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2edfe335-1ec4-4826-b56b-47a4e7f35856","outputTokens":390,"requestId":"7403:3C1523:1D54B97:207014B:6A052489"},"id":"f658ecdd-a320-407e-9d93-6792997bd414","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:25:40.733Z","parentId":"2713e7bc-be8c-42de-a2a0-cefad78d2f00"}
